 <strong>October 26,  2013</strong><p><i>Orange County Register</i><p><strong>Virtual Reality: Not Just a Game</strong><p><strong>By: Ian Hamilton</strong><br><p>

<style>

   IMG.wrapped_image        { width: 260px; padding-bottom: 1em; }
   IMG.wrapped_image.right  { float: right; padding-left: 1em; }
   IMG.wrapped_image.left   { float: left; padding-right: 1em; }

</style>






<!--<P>
<I>Read the full story below or view it on the <A HREF="http://www.ocregister.com/articles/ ">Orange County Register website</A>.</I>
<P>-->



<P>
<I>Oculus Rift goggles popping up in more practical applications.</I>




<P>
The $300 goggles that Irvine-based
Oculus VR began shipping to software developers
in March deliver a glimpse of a futuristic
technology long awaited by video
gamers. They allow a player
to step inside a computercreated
virtual world.
<P>
What might be most eyeopening,
though, is how the
Oculus Rift goggles are finding
their way into nongaming
applications.
<P>
Architects have found
ways to visualize houses that
haven&rsquo;t been constructed
yet. A manufacturer in Indiana sees a way
to save money by demonstrating its products
without having to transport them
across the country. NASA believes it could
use virtual reality to let scientists and the
public explore the landscape on the surface
of Mars without setting foot in a spaceship.
<P>
The goggles themselves are still a work
in progress. In its current version, the Rift
delivers a relatively low-resolution experience
that doesn&rsquo;t yet track the full range of
human motion. As a result, some people
get motion sickness.
<P>
&ldquo;Many people find wandering around
with a head-mounted display in a 3D stereoscopic
world disconcerting,&rdquo; said Walt
Scacchi, research director at UC Irvine&rsquo;s
Institute for Virtual Environments and
Computer Games. He&rsquo;s one of them. However,
Scacchi is confident that improvements
in technologies such as increased
screen resolution and reduced delay in image
display &ldquo;will bring us closer to consumer-
ready, immersive 3D stereoscopic displays.&rdquo;



<P>
Oculus is using $16 million
in venture capital it
raised in June to hire virtual
reality experts to solve
those and other problems.
One of their tasks is to get
feedback from users of the
more than 35,000 developer
kits they&rsquo;ve sold to date.
Oculus is also counting on
those developers to write
the software that puts people
in other worlds once it
becomes consumer-ready.
<P>
The Register asked several
people who&rsquo;ve tried the
Rift in different industries
to describe how they&rsquo;re using
virtual reality &ndash; and
what&rsquo;s holding the technology
back.


<P>
<B>WALKING ON MARS</B>
<P>
Jeff Norris is a computer
scientist leading the Mission
Operations Innovation
Office at the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena, a
lab focused on projects that
can change the way humans
interact with and control
spacecraft. Prior to that he
worked on development of
the rover Curiosity and the
uplink system used to command
it.
<P>
&ldquo;One of the things we&rsquo;re
investigating is the use of
immersive displays for
looking at data returned
from spacecraft. We&rsquo;re
looking at virtual reality
technology as a way for our
scientists and engineers to
better understand the environment
around a spacecraft
and then better control
that spacecraft.
<P>
&ldquo;But we&rsquo;re also looking at
these technologies as a way
to share the journey of
these missions with the
public. The fact that [inexpensive
devices like the
Rift] are becoming more accessible
to a broader audience
helps both those goals.
<P>
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s now conceivable to
put these kinds of devices in
the hands of a whole mission
science team. It&rsquo;s also
possible for us to imagine in
the not too distant future
millions of people in the
public having these kinds of
devices and being able to
consume this data along
with us.&rdquo;
<P>
One NASA demo takes
information from Curiosity
on Mars and turns it into
panoramic views, as if you
were sitting on the vehicle
looking around. Another
lets you move around the
International Space Station,
in 3D, using an Xbox
controller.
<P>
&ldquo;If we put humans on
Mars someday, we should
have millions of people
there with them standing
beside them in this &lsquo;holodeck&rsquo;-
like way. In 1969, the
television was the most engaging
and effective medium
for bringing the world
along. It was the perfect
choice at the time. It&rsquo;s not
the perfect choice now.&rdquo;


<P>
<B>BACK TO SCHOOL</B>
<P>
Matt Bell is CEO of a
Mountain View firm, Matterport,
that has raised $10
million to build a camera
that can make an accurate
3D model of rooms and other
interior spaces and share
it online. Imagine redecorating
your home virtually,
before pulling the trigger
on anything.
<P>
&ldquo;One of my favorite experiences
with the Rift was
when viewing a model of a
preschool (whose images)
we had captured. I had the
idea to change the user
height to be three feet so
that I could experience the
preschool as a preschooler.
It brought a flood of memories
back &ndash; masses of toys
scattered across the
ground, with posters on
high walls and countertops
out of reach.
<P>
&ldquo;That was in July of this
year. I&rsquo;ve never been to the
preschool itself; I&rsquo;ve only
experienced it online. We
imaged the entire preschool,
which consisted of
several large rooms. It took
about 90 minutes to capture
everything. Processing
the data into a 3D model
was fully automatic and
took about 30 minutes.&rdquo;


<P>
<B>LOSE THE TANKS</B>
<P>
Jay Fuller works for Wessels
Co., a company near Indianapolis
that makes pressure
vessels. Those are
enormous containers, up to
12 feet across, that cost
thousands to buy and might
be used as part of a drinking-
water or water-heating
system.
<P>
&ldquo;We do a couple large industry
tradeshows a year,
which involves shipping out
some of our very large, very
heavy tanks back and forth
between convention halls.
As you can imagine, that
can get pretty expensive.
So I thought wouldn&rsquo;t it be
cool if we could bring
around a virtual reality
warehouse demo showcasing
some of our larger tank
models to some of these
shows.
<P>
&ldquo;Because we model all of
our tanks in 3D using Solid-
Works&rdquo; &ndash; a modeling software
program &ndash; &ldquo;it was a
relatively painless process
of converting them into
meshes suitable for the Unity
game engine,&rdquo; said Fuller,
referring to a popular
video game development
toolkit that works with the
Rift. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re planning to
premiere the finished demo
at our biggest tradeshow,&rdquo;
the AHR Expo in New York
in January.


<P>
<B>THE VIRTUAL ARCHITECT</B>
<P>
Jon Brouchoud has a
master&rsquo;s in architecture
and is the lead developer at
his consultancy firm Arch
Virtual, based in Wisconsin.
He was hired to make
3D walkthroughs of buildings
for Web browsers before
the Rift came along,
but now has a steady
stream of projects for clients
that include architects,
real estate developers,
corporations and universities
porting the work
to the fully immersive Oculus
gear.
<P>
&ldquo;We&rsquo;ve been focusing on
short and sweet experiences.
We&rsquo;re finding that just
putting an Oculus Rift on
someone is enough all by itself
to just blow people
away. There&rsquo;s a bit of overhyping
in terms of game development.
It might just be
because I&rsquo;m not a game developer.
I don&rsquo;t see people
wearing this for extended
periods of time playing long
game experiences &ndash; firstperson
shooters, where
they&rsquo;re running around.
<P>
&ldquo;Most of the clients we&rsquo;re
showing these projects,
they&rsquo;ve never been in the
Oculus Rift before. We
bring them in there and
they&rsquo;re not prepared to
spend 20 minutes walking
around inside of it. Two or
three minutes is about all
they can handle. Luckily,
that&rsquo;s all they really need.
You want to stand inside the
lobby of a new building
that&rsquo;s about to be constructed
&ndash; you just stand
there, look around, walk
around, take the experience
in.
<P>
&ldquo;Almost every one of
them is blown away. I&rsquo;d say
one in maybe 30 or 40 people
just don&rsquo;t seem to get it.
We went around and did demos
with architects all over
Chicago and San Francisco
&ndash; like 100 architects tried it
on. Out of those there were
maybe one or two that were like, &rsquo;eh.&rsquo;&rdquo;









